The article is a presidential proclamation from April 27, 2009, declaring April 26 to May 2 as National Crime Victims' Rights Week. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of protecting families and fighting crime. It acknowledges the efforts of individuals working to reduce crime and support victims. The Victims of Crime Act of 1984 is mentioned as a significant achievement in providing assistance to crime victims. The American Recovery and Reinvestment Act is also mentioned for providing funding to law enforcement personnel. The proclamation highlights the importance of prisoner reentry programs in reducing crime recidivism. The president calls upon all Americans to observe the week by raising awareness of victims' rights and volunteering to serve victims in their time of need.